# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1867-spanish-general-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] General elections to the special Cortes of Cádiz were held in Spain in 1810.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 276 seats in the Cortes of Cádiz – which served as a parliamentary Regency after Ferdinand VII was deposed by Napoleon.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] During the first years of the Spanish War of Independence (1808-1814) the popular revolts of the Spanish people were accompanied by the creation of provincial and local defense "Juntas".
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] Those juntas assumed national sovereignty, forming their own local and regional governing bodies.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] These juntas aimed to defend against the French invasion and fill the power vacuum, refusing to recognize José I Bonaparte as their legitimate king.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] The juntas were mainly composed of military personnel, representatives of the high clergy, officials and professors.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] In September 1808 the local and provincial juntas ceded their power to the Supreme Central Government Junta of the Kingdom, which led the war against the French and was recognized as the legitimate government of Spain by the United Kingdom and other anti-Napoleonic countries.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] The Supreme Junta summoned an extraordinary meeting of the Cortes of Cádiz, a revolutionary act, since the right to call for a meeting of the Cortes was exclusive to the crown.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] After an intense debate in the Supreme Junta it was decided that the Cortes of Cádiz would be unicameral, elected by census suffrage (only those with a certain level of income could vote) and indirect.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] The Cortes met for the first time in the last major Spanish foothold during the Peninsular War, Cádiz, on the Isla de León, on September 24, 1810.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 32 multi-member constituencies and 2 single-member constituencies.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] All male citizens above 25 years old could vote or be voted.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1813.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 149 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] The 1813 elections were the first ones held since the approval of the 1812 Cádiz Constitution.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] All males over 21 years old, a total of 3,216,460 people, had the right to vote.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1820.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 203 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] The 1820 elections were the first ones since the 1820 revolution.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] The elections were held under the Spanish Constitution of 1812.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 33 multi-member constituencies and various single-member ones.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] Most MPs were liberals, mainly from the *moderate* (or *doceañista*) faction.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1822.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] The 1822 elections were the second ones since the 1820 revolution.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] 3,215,460 people were eligible to vote (universal male suffrage), out of a population of 11,661,865.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] Almost all MPs were liberals, mainly from the radical *veinteañista* or *exaltada* faction.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1834.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 188 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] The 1834 elections were the first ones since 1822 and signalled the return of liberalism to Spain after the absolutist Década Ominosa.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] The elections were held under the Spanish Royal Statute of 1834, not under a full constitutional system.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] A first-past-the-post system was used with 48 multi-member constituencies and one single-member constituency.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] Only around 18,000 people were allowed to vote, out of a population of 12 million.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in November 1837.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 241 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] Restricted census suffrage, only 262,000 people out of a total population of 12,162,872 were allowed to vote.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] The elections were held on 22 September, at the peak of the First Carlist War.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 51 multi-member constituencies and 1 single-member constituency.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1839-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain on 24 July 1839.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1839-spanish-general-election] Restricted census suffrage, only 376,255 people out of a total population of 12,162,872 were allowed to vote.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1839-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 48 multi-member constituencies and 1 single-member constituency.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1867-spanish-general-election] A general election was held in Spain from 10 to 13 March 1867 to elect the members of the 10th Cortes under the Spanish Constitution of 1845.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1867-spanish-general-election] 352 seats in the Congress of Deputies were up for election.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1867-spanish-general-election] Less than 400,000 people were eligible to vote, about 2.6% of the total population.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1867-spanish-general-election] The election was mostly uncontested by opposition parties, with many candidates from the ruling Moderate Party running unopposed.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1867-spanish-general-election] Under the 1845 Constitution, the Spanish Cortes were conceived as "co-legislative bodies", forming a nearly perfect bicameral system.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1867-spanish-general-election] The term of the Congress expired five years from the date of its previous election, unless it was dissolved earlier.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1867-spanish-general-election] Election day was held over four voting days: the first was used to elect polling station officials, and the remaining three were devoted to the parliamentary election itself.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1867-spanish-general-election] The monarch had the prerogative to dissolve Congress at any given time and call a snap election.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1867-spanish-general-election] The Congress was officially dissolved on 30 December 1866, with the corresponding decree setting election day to start on 10 March 1867 and scheduling for the chamber to reconvene on 30 March.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1867-spanish-general-election] In the Basque Provinces and Navarre—where taxes were not paid directly—voters had instead to prove wealth equivalent to an income of 450 escudos (in capital or property).
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1867-spanish-general-election] Additional restrictions excluded those deprived of political rights or barred from public office by a final sentence, criminally imprisoned or convicted, legally incapacitated, bankrupt, and public debtors.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1867-spanish-general-election] The Congress of Deputies had one seat per 45,000 inhabitants or fraction above 22,500.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1867-spanish-general-election] All were elected in multi-member constituencies corresponding to the provinces of Spain—each assigned a number of seats according to population—using two-round majority voting.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1867-spanish-general-election] Provinces above 337,500 inhabitants were divided into two or more sub-provincial constituencies (with no province electing more than seven seats), whereas municipalities over 45,000 inhabitants were to form an independent constituency each.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1867-spanish-general-election] The law provided for by-elections to fill vacant seats during the legislative term, as long as this affected at least one third of the seats assigned to a given constituency.
[src:1867-spanish-general-election/1867-spanish-general-election] For the Congress, secular Spanish males of voting age, taxpayers for any direct tax, could run for election.
